'''Shōmonji''' (声聞師)

== Summary ==
Shōmonji (声聞師) refers to Japanese performers who existed during the {{ill|Medieval Japan|ja|中世|12=draft}} period (12th to 16th century). They practiced mystical performing arts derived from the culture of {{ill|Onmyōji|ja|陰陽師|12=draft}}, including {{ill|Buddhist chanting|ja|読経|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kusemai|ja|曲舞|12=draft}}, {{ill|Divination|ja|卜占|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Sarugaku|ja|猿楽|12=draft}}, all forms of ritualistic and celebratory performances. The term "Shōmonji" can also be read as "Shōmoji," with alternate kanji variations like 唱門師, 唱聞師, 聖問師, 唱文師, and 誦文師.

== History and Overview ==
According to {{ill|Takahashi Masaaki|ja|高橋昌明|12=draft}}, Shōmonji engaged in drumming, distributing calendars, performing divination, and various magical arts. They were considered missionaries spreading water-related folklore.

{{ill|Yanagita Kunio|ja|柳田國男|12=draft}} equated Shōmonji with figures like "Hakase" (民間の陰陽師), "Onmyōji," "Manzai," "Kugutsu," "Sanjodayu," "Dengaku-hōshi," "Kaneuchi," and "Hachitakaki."

Their arts trace back to the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|12=draft}} (7th-10th century), originally practiced by officials under the {{ill|Onmyō-ryō|ja|陰陽寮|12=draft}}. Despite similarities, Shōmonji were entertainers rather than religious figures.

