'''Shōmonji''' (声聞師)

== Summary ==
Shōmonji (声聞師) refers to Japanese performers who existed during the {{ill|Medieval Japan|ja|中世|qq=draft|qq=draft}} period (12th to 16th century). They practiced mystical performing arts derived from the culture of {{ill|Onmyōji|ja|陰陽師|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, including {{ill|Buddhist chanting|ja|読経|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Kusemai|ja|曲舞|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, {{ill|Divination|ja|卜占|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, and {{ill|Sarugaku|ja|猿楽|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, all forms of ritualistic and celebratory performances. The term "Shōmonji" can also be read as "Shōmoji," with alternate kanji variations like 唱門師, 唱聞師, 聖問師, 唱文師, and 誦文師.

== History and Overview ==
According to {{ill|Takahashi Masaaki|ja|高橋昌明|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, Shōmonji engaged in drumming, distributing calendars, performing divination, and various magical arts. They were considered missionaries spreading water-related folklore.

{{ill|Yanagita Kunio|ja|柳田國男|qq=draft|qq=draft}} equated Shōmonji with figures like "Hakase" (民間の陰陽師), "Onmyōji," "Manzai," "Kugutsu," "Sanjodayu," "Dengaku-hōshi," "Kaneuchi," and "Hachitakaki."

Their arts trace back to the {{ill|Ritsuryō system|ja|律令制|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (7th-10th century), originally practiced by officials under the {{ill|Onmyō-ryō|ja|陰陽寮|1=Yin-Yang Bureau|2=ja|3=陰陽寮|4=fr|5=Bureau d'Onmyō|6=zh|7=阴阳寮|8=ko|9=음양료|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Despite similarities, Shōmonji were entertainers rather than religious figures.

